>>50689008
I just moved out of south Florida last year after living there my whole life. I've lived through many hurricanes.
>getting washed out into the wetlands and swamps by a hurricane
Hurricanes are powerful, but at the same time absolutely benign if you're in a real house or apartment. Only people within a mile of the ocean or in a mobile home ever need to worry during a hurricane. Hurricanes are also slow enough to not be a surprise.
Everything in your story will have to depend on what time period you set it in. In the modern time, hurricanes cause lots of property damage and financial damage but very few deaths and very little personal danger, in Florida.
The only scary part about hurricanes is that they can spawn tornadoes, and tornadoes are truly scary.

You need something beyond a hurricane. I think the other anon's airboat idea could work. Perhaps your protagonist messed up in his own way (while a hurricane is still predicted to be a couple days out) and then while still messed up, the hurricane comes and he needs to shelter indoors with the waifur.
Sheltering indoors with her is only necessary during the hurricane, and for the very immediate time right before and after it. I can't imagine any sort of bridge or road damage like another poster suggested. Perhaps the waifur prioritizes fixing some of her own stuff after the hurricane rather than returning the protagonist to civilization, even though she's capable of doing it the day after the hurricane.

I'm from south Florida. Rednecks only exist in north Florida and central Florida, if it matters. In the everglades of south Florida you'd be more likely to meet a native American or a white guy involved in native-American-related tourism than a redneck.

Anonymous Mon 05 Sep 2022 16:23:23 No.50704206 Report
Quoted By: >>50704562
>>50703309
If you're the guy that was talking a few threads ago about the waifur that goes on rants about various subjects, here's my advice.
Figure out her thoughts, stat. If it's nagging you that they feel like a mess, then it's also up to you to make them seem coherent from her POV. And after that, her motivations. One of the things I've noticed in very recent fantasy, and especially in the Amazon/Netflix stuff, is that motivations are one-dimensional if there at all.
A well-rounded character has long-term goals that need to be pieced together from short-term successes (which are not always the way they'd planned), and those from very immediate needs which trump everything. How they deal with that progression is their mindset, and the sooner you grasp that, the easier it is to drop into the character.
I hate sounding like a lecture on things you might already know, but a good framework lets you pants and come up with better characters.

>>50704562
My point is this: you have to accept that the reader might not bother reading all those thoughts. Doesn't matter if you think it makes sense. Your job is to get the reader to accept it.

So to simplify her, I'd do the following if that was the list in front of me.
Something triggers a thought on her family history, and that tips into how past civilizations managed to keep control via taxation & religion. The thought caps on why her civilization works, or what is going wrong (if there is a rebellion, for instance)
The crops and uses are a single thought, but can be revisited as needed. After all, food is at the heart of controlling the population.
Getting killed and the next three can bundle into external security, and medicine can call back to farming in general; a healthy people are better at fighting.
From her fiance's scent onward is one idea.

The gist is that you have things that are practically related to each other, so you can have a logical flow between them or, if needed, called back from a different angle.
This is something I struggled with in creating my setting. Once I linked up ideas, I realized what certain factions had to be like and that grounded the characters. As I wrote the characters, I went back and fleshed out the society.
So basic setting -> characters <-> society -> world. I originally started here to learn to write so I could make the settings in my head come alive. In the years since, I've decided the atom of a story & setting is the character. Thus the term chemistry is an apt joke.
